# Cross-Platform Targeting

This is an Electron desktop app that must run on **macOS, Windows, and Linux**. Every implementation decision must account for all three platforms.

## Platform-Aware Patterns

- Use `process.platform` (exposed as `window.electronAPI.platform` in the renderer) to branch platform-specific behavior
- Use the `data-platform` attribute on `<html>` for CSS platform targeting (e.g. `:root[data-platform="darwin"]`)
- Never use Unix-only shell commands in npm scripts (no `unset`, `rm -rf`, etc.) — use Node.js scripts or `cross-env` equivalents
- Use `path.join()` or `path.sep` instead of hardcoded `/` separators in file paths

## Electron Specifics

- `titleBarStyle: 'hidden'` is used on all platforms
- macOS uses `transparent: false` and a solid `backgroundColor` matching app chrome (avoids a 1px edge artifact with `transparent` + vibrancy); traffic light positioning is set via `trafficLightPosition`
- Windows/Linux get `titleBarOverlay` with themed colors and native minimize/maximize/close controls
- The `ELECTRON_RUN_AS_NODE` env var is handled by `scripts/electron-vite.js` — do not add platform-specific workarounds to npm scripts
- Use standard `electron` imports (not `electron/main` or `electron/renderer`) for cross-platform module resolution

## File System

- File paths are case-sensitive on Linux, case-insensitive on macOS/Windows — never rely on case to distinguish files
- Use `app.getPath()` for platform-appropriate config/data directories
- Line endings may differ (`\n` vs `\r\n`) — handle gracefully when reading/writing files

## Testing

- Any UI or system-level change should be validated (or at minimum considered) on all three platforms before closing out
